<paragraph blockId="24.[189,508,311,338]" box="[189,508,311,338]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">BODY LENGTH. 7.0–8.0 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,872,376,403]" box="[189,872,376,403]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
BODY. Robust; only macropterous morphs known (
<figureCitation box="[785,857,376,403]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="23.[189,232,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,316,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-11@23.[189,1398,316,1753]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Fig. 5. Dorsal habitus of species of Gerbelius Distant, 1903. Scale bars = 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846646" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846646/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1339,442,468]" box="[189,1339,442,468]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">COLORATION. Variable color patterns; scutellum uniform or with contrasting yellow scutellar spine.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[188,1401,507,710]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
INTEGUMENT AND VESTITURE. Head and pronotum: smooth to corrugated with dense pubescence and sparse, long macrosetae; antennifer with macroseta, without lateral protuberance (
<figureCitation box="[1144,1237,542,569]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1710,1736]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,339,1657]" captionTargetId="figure-11@11.[189,1398,339,1657]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 3. Morphological characters. A–D. Head in dorsal view. A. Gerbelius nr. confluens. B. Voconia decorata sp. nov. C. Voconia pallidipes Stål, 1866. D. Voconia schoutedeni (Villiers, 1964) comb. nov. E–G. Head in lateral view. E. Voconia wegneri (Miller, 1954) comb. nov. F. Voconia dolichocephala sp. nov. G. Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903. H. Voconia loki sp. nov., head and pronotum in dorsal view. I–J. Prosternum in ventrolateral view. I. Voconia mexicana sp. nov. J. Voconia bracata sp. nov. K–L. Pronotum in dorsal view. K. Voconia conradti (Jeannel, 1917) comb. nov. L. Voconia tuberculata sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846642/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
); labium with dense, long macrosetae. Thorax: anterolateral angles of pronotal collar with macrosetae. Hemelytron: corium with dense setation. Legs: posterior row of protuberances on mid and hind femora with three large spines on distal half and three or fewer small spines. Abdomen: ventral surface pubescent with long macrosetae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[188,1400,749,1128]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
HEAD (
<figureCitation box="[273,408,749,775]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1710,1736]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,339,1657]" captionTargetId="figure-11@11.[189,1398,339,1657]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 3. Morphological characters. A–D. Head in dorsal view. A. Gerbelius nr. confluens. B. Voconia decorata sp. nov. C. Voconia pallidipes Stål, 1866. D. Voconia schoutedeni (Villiers, 1964) comb. nov. E–G. Head in lateral view. E. Voconia wegneri (Miller, 1954) comb. nov. F. Voconia dolichocephala sp. nov. G. Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903. H. Voconia loki sp. nov., head and pronotum in dorsal view. I–J. Prosternum in ventrolateral view. I. Voconia mexicana sp. nov. J. Voconia bracata sp. nov. K–L. Pronotum in dorsal view. K. Voconia conradti (Jeannel, 1917) comb. nov. L. Voconia tuberculata sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846642/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 3A, G</figureCitation>
). Elongate, 1.2–1.3 times as long as wide; anteocular region about a third of head length and shorter than postocular region (measured to anterior margin of neck); postocular region in dorsal view globose and longer than eye; pedicel 1.1–1.3 times length of head width; mandibular plates in dorsal view long with basal half adjacent; maxillary plates in dorsal view enlarged laterally forming flattened projections, adjacent to clypeus; clypeus width in dorsal view narrower than maxillary plates; interocular glabrous markings V-shaped, joined medially at interocular sulcus; eye width in dorsal view narrower than synthlipsis, eye not reaching ventral head margin in lateral view; ventrolateral swelling of buccula without lateral protrusion that surpasses buccular margin, flat margin; labium stout; second (first visible) labial segment in lateral view surpassing posteroventral eye margin, gradually widened apically; dorsal surface of third (second visible) labial segment convex, 0.8–0.9 times length of second segment; fourth (third visible) labial segment drawn into bent, slender apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[187,1399,1166,1298]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">THORAX. Pronotal collar narrow medially with anterolateral angles short and flared laterally; anterior pronotal lobe lateral margins rounded; scutellum width 0.8 times length; scutellar spine subhorizontal; anteriad-directed process on prosternum with paramedial lobes; anterior margin of stridulitrum projected into sharp spine; proepimeron with obtuse protuberance on posteroventral margin.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1387,1337,1370]" box="[189,1387,1337,1370]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
HEMELYTRON (
<figureCitation box="[354,448,1337,1364]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[189,232,1805,1831]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,589,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-109@13.[189,1398,589,1767]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 4. Morphological characters. A–D. Scutellum and hemelytron, dorsal view. A. Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903.B. Voconia lirophleps sp. nov. C. Voconia bracata sp. nov.D. Voconia schoutedeni (Villiers, 1964) comb. nov. E. Voconia grandioculata sp. nov., thorax, lateral view. F–H. Voconia nyx sp. nov. F. Thorax, lateral view. G. Fore tibia, ventral view. H. Mid tibia and tarsus, ventral view. I–K. Hind femur, posterior view. I. Voconia mexicana sp. nov. J. Voconia decorata sp. nov. K. Voconia bracata sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846644" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846644/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Cu-An 
<subScript attach="left" box="[548,557,1356,1370]" fontSize="6" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">1</subScript>
cell similar in size to M-Cu cell; Cu-An 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1031,1040,1356,1370]" fontSize="6" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">1</subScript>
cell slender, tapered apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1398,1403,1464]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">LEGS. Fossula spongiosa present on fore and mid legs in males, present on fore but absent or vestigial on mid legs of females.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1398,1503,1565]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">ABDOMEN. Anterior margin of terga weakly carinulate; terga II and III with paired, prominent, and longitudinal carinae, almost reaching posterior margin of tergum III.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1398,1604,1666]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
PYGOPHORE (
<figureCitation box="[339,428,1604,1630]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="42.[189,232,1934,1960]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,303,1877]" captionTargetId="figure-14@42.[189,1398,301,1877]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Fig. 11. Pygophore of species of Gerbelius Distant, 1903 and Voconia Stål, 1866. Median apical process of Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903 and V. bakeri sp. nov. damaged/missing. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846660/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Transverse bridge rounded on posterior margin; lateral pygophore margin flat; paramere shape in dorsal view sinusoidal, apex tapered into squarely round tip.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1398,1704,1766]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
AEDEAGUS (
<figureCitation box="[330,422,1704,1731]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="79.[189,232,1890,1916]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,280,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-11@79.[189,1398,279,1838]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Fig. 15. Pygophore of outgroup species. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846670" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846670/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Endosoma almost entirely covered with spicules; apex of dorsal phallothecal sclerite rounded in dorsal view; basal plate extension 4.4–4.8 times as long as wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,342,1805,1831]" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1805,1831]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[189,1399,1852,1949]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
This genus currently comprises two described species from 
<collectingCountry box="[890,950,1852,1878]" name="India" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">India</collectingCountry>
and Southeast Asia, and we are aware of at least four undescribed species distributed across 
<collectingCountry box="[842,905,1887,1913]" name="India" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[919,979,1887,1913]" name="Laos" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Laos</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[993,1100,1887,1913]" name="Thailand" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1166,1269,1887,1913]" name="Vietnam" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Gerbelius typicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most widespread among them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[189,303,265,291]" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[187,1400,311,690]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Photographs of 
<typeStatus box="[370,421,312,338]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
specimens in their unit trays at the BMNH were used to evaluate species concepts for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[187,304,347,373]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typicus">
<emphasis box="[187,304,347,373]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">G. typicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[357,502,346,373]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confluens">
<emphasis box="[357,502,346,373]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">G. confluens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This genus previously had a third described species that is now transferred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[187,282,382,407]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Voconia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[187,282,382,407]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Voconia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Castillo &amp; Rédei &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Distant" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[298,405,382,407]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Voconia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis box="[298,405,382,407]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">V. ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Molecular phylogenetics recovered a 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[861,977,381,407]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[861,977,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade (
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1242,381,408]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-3">
<emphasis box="[1063,1179,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
sp. 3
</taxonomicName>
+ [
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-1">
<emphasis box="[1283,1399,381,407]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
sp. 1
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName box="[269,445,416,443]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-4">
<emphasis box="[269,385,417,443]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
sp. 4
</taxonomicName>
]) sister to 
<taxonomicName authority="Castillo &amp; Rédei &amp; Weirauch, 2022" authorityName="Castillo &amp; Rédei &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Miller" baseAuthorityYear="1954" box="[560,755,417,442]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Voconia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wegneri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[560,755,417,442]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Voconia wegneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[762,850,417,443]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hwang W. S. &amp; Weirauch C." box="[863,1170,417,443]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="45523" refId="ref51461" refString="Hwang W. S. &amp; Weirauch C. 2012. Evolutionary history of assassin bugs (Insecta: Hemiptera: Reduviidae): Insights from divergence dating and ancestral state reconstruction. PLoS ONE 7 (9): e 45523. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0045523" type="journal article" year="2012">Hwang &amp; Weirauch, 2012</bibRefCitation>
). We also recovered a well-supported 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[397,513,452,478]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[397,513,452,478]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade sister to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1866" box="[695,790,453,478]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Voconia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[695,790,453,478]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Voconia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[805,913,452,478]" captionStart-0="Fig" captionStart-1="Fig" captionStartId-0="8.[190,233,1950,1976]" captionStartId-1="9.[189,232,1883,1909]" captionTargetBox-0="[204,1371,808,1898]" captionTargetBox-1="[199,1395,651,1845]" captionTargetId-0="figure-168@8.[189,1398,793,1908]" captionTargetId-1="figure-137@9.[189,1398,644,1845]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionText-0="Fig. 1. Strict consensus tree resulting from equal weighting analysis. Jackknife values over 51 are reported for tree one of eight." captionText-1="Fig. 2. Tree resulting from implied weighting analysis using K = 12 with characters unambiguously optimized. Symmetric resampling values over 51 are represented for trees obtained with K = 3, K = 6, K = 9, and K = 12 analyses. Characters and character states are described in pp. 11–22. Specimens not to scale." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846638" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846640" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5846638/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5846640/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
). The pygophore of 
<specimenCount box="[1157,1332,452,478]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
were dissected for this study (
<figureCitation box="[482,573,487,513]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="42.[189,232,1934,1960]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,303,1877]" captionTargetId="figure-14@42.[189,1398,301,1877]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Fig. 11. Pygophore of species of Gerbelius Distant, 1903 and Voconia Stål, 1866. Median apical process of Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903 and V. bakeri sp. nov. damaged/missing. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846660/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs 11</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[587,619,487,513]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="75.[188,231,1989,2015]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,760,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-180@75.[189,1397,760,1946]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Fig. 14. Aedeagus of species of Gerbelius Distant, 1903 and Voconia Stål, 1866. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846668" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846668/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">14</figureCitation>
); however, the median apical process of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[1109,1229,487,513]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="typicus">
<emphasis box="[1109,1229,487,513]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">G. typicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(AMNH_IZC 00321200) broke off during dissection (
<figureCitation box="[662,749,522,548]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="42.[189,232,1934,1960]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,303,1877]" captionTargetId="figure-14@42.[189,1398,301,1877]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Fig. 11. Pygophore of species of Gerbelius Distant, 1903 and Voconia Stål, 1866. Median apical process of Gerbelius typicus Distant, 1903 and V. bakeri sp. nov. damaged/missing. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5846660" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5846660/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). We decided not to describe new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[1284,1400,522,548]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1284,1400,522,548]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as part of this study. Since species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1903" box="[642,758,557,583]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Gerbelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[642,758,557,583]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Gerbelius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
somewhat resemble other small-bodied assassin bugs currently classified as Reduviinae, we suspect that our specimen searches in various natural history collections were not comprehensive for this genus. However, this material should be included in a future revision of this genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
